<subsection xml:id="subsec-probability-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Probability in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_cdphsa6r">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_qul6slzd">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4c5zit5e">
                        3.0 Statistics and Probability
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_k4jk0faz">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_65rzvyjx">
                        3.2 Probability 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nn6tm83t">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v4i96n6j">
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_24z7d1v7">Identify the range of probability in different situations</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_49s1f4wn">Appreciate the application of probability in real-life situations</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_89gplssl" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_mdn75cr2">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jvlus3al" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1ja3bgqx">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_gb72y5qw" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_vctareim"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_egr7f9oy">
                        <p xml:id="auto_e80w61r6">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand how probability is used to make decisions and predictions in various real-world fields.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jqr63d0y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5zyiayfm">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply probability concepts to analyse and solve real-life scenarios.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_if3a985d">
                        <p xml:id="auto_f6q9ew8g">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Appreciate the role of probability in fields such as weather forecasting, medicine, sports, and business.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_28wtrs4r">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/probability-1/probability-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hzy35p22">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/probability-1/step-by-step-guide_probability-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_nehn5csj">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_t1ky9nm8">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_qesxh3ks">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2jdabz9x">
                    Learners work in groups to explore how probability is used in real-life decision-making through a weather station scenario.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_jeg400tq"><p xml:id="auto_36ukcior">What probability did your group assign? How did you decide?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yldaauk3"><p xml:id="auto_oji7gxfq">Did different groups get different probabilities? Why?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hmxb7l0m"><p xml:id="auto_d9akwqk1">How would a farmer use this probability to make decisions?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kcxee494"><p xml:id="auto_alvoupbo">Does a 70% chance of rain mean it will definitely rain?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lqj7igwx"><p xml:id="auto_sgxial2m">What other real-life decisions involve probability?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_phjyoeo9">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_4sveywup">
            <p xml:id="auto_yhqi72nb">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qun2ogup">
                Grade <m>10</m> learners went on a field trip to a weather station to learn about how meteorologists use probability to predict the weather.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0j3kaxwm">
                The weather forecast says:
                There is a <m>70\%</m> chance of rain tomorrow.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_svn7ueqy">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jnnmkb8n">
                    What does <m>70\%</m> probability mean?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dcihohx0">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bd9uikse">
                    Should students carry an umbrella? Why?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_yt1sdb78">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_wcrwpmdn">
                     Does <m>70\%</m> probability guarantee that it will rain? Explain your answer.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_l81rc8jp">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_owvmjtlr">
                    What could happen if you ignore the probability?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_wper7zse">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hy3o99g8">
                    How do people use probability in daily life without realising it?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dermdlil">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_l5hb6cir">
                    Share your work with the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8yff1qhy">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ygjrourw">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_p14yj7sq">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_uh9hzbtq">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_itcxltg5">
                    To formalize the applications of probability in real-world contexts including weather, insurance, medicine, sports, and business.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_ytekqabe">
        <p xml:id="auto_x5l59mq5">
            Probability is used in real-life situations to make predictions and informed decisions.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8w92t3xl">
            For example,  
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_zep6qker">
                    <p xml:id="auto_pnpd58dy">
                        In weather forecasting, meteorologists use probability to predict the likelihood of rain, sunshine, or storms.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_24u9797f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6pp12p3w">
                        In sports, coaches and analysts use probability to assess the chances of winning a game or making a successful play. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xkf32ba7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9lnoplaj">
                        In quality control, manufacturers use probability to determine the likelihood of defects in their products and to improve their production processes.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sul5e0gm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dnn464sh">
                        In traffic management, authorities use probability to analyze traffic patterns and make decisions about road construction and traffic light timing.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_y1fsfnwf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_q2q30ktc">
                         In gambling, players use probability to calculate the odds of winning a bet or a lottery.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jd7ol54m">
                    <p xml:id="auto_iyzkv1ll">
                        In healthcare, doctors use probability to assess the risk of diseases and determine the best treatment options for patients.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vu833fdf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xmn1rq6t">
                        In finance, investors use probability to evaluate the potential returns and risks of different investments.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lri1e7nc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xrnmmwkl">
                        In elections, political analysts use probability to predict the outcome of elections based on polling data and historical trends.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iwlv5ajb">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9ifw3i0k">
                        In everyday decision-making, individuals use probability to assess the risks and benefits of various choices, such as whether to carry an umbrella or not based on the chance of rain.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_76imdd8g">
            By applying the concepts of probability, we can better understand and navigate the uncertainties of the world around us, making more informed decisions in our personal and professional lives.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3p61ovnj">
             
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_l3gllrdx">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_i7nxecfd">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5tyuzuxj">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_jsz8utab">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rv0oimuq">
                    To apply probability concepts to real-life scenarios and calculations.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_6bt8xd18">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5ga5eard">
                    Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_213gxyyy">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_r70dzf6g">
                A class of <m>30</m> students is planning a revision session for their upcoming exams. 
                They have three time slots to choose from: <m>4</m> PM, <m>5</m> PM, and <m>6</m> PM. 
                The students were asked to vote for their preferred time slot, and the results are as follows:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_qrkolq1m">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qksyiyy3">
                            <m>12</m> students prefer <m>4</m> PM
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_q1hp4uw4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_n90ama4i">
                            <m>10</m> students prefer <m>5</m> PM
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_rgdshslv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_oy2bfomq">
                            <m>8</m> students prefer <m>6</m> PM
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_62bhn5vj">
                Based on the votes, determine the probability of each time slot being chosen for the revision session.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_02b3g7jd">
                To find the probability of each time slot being chosen, we divide the number of votes for each time slot by the total number of students (<m>30</m>).
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mxtmsub4">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_f73d5yql">
                    <p xml:id="auto_o8svd0tr">
                        Probability of <m>4</m> PM <m>= \frac{12}{30} = \frac{2}{5} = 0.4</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zbxefoqr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_vns99q2z">
                        Probability of <m>5</m> PM <m>= \frac{10}{30} = \frac{1}{3} \approx 0.33</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pafz5t3w">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l1xclvuw">
                        Probability of <m>6</m> PM <m>= \frac{8}{30} = \frac{4}{15} \approx 0.27</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5ic83mkt">
                Therefore, the probabilities of each time slot being chosen are:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_x8pfus6t">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3upuuc56">
                            <m>4</m> PM: <m>0.4</m> (<m>40\%</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lp8j3s9n">
                        <p xml:id="auto_del1owry">
                            <m>5</m> PM: <m>0.33</m> (<m>33\%</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bnr3vjrg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d1r4virs">
                            <m>6</m> PM: <m>0.27</m> (<m>27\%</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_pbymy196">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_2z7oisqj">
                A weather forecast predicts a <m>60\%</m> chance of rain tomorrow. 
                If you have an outdoor event planned, what is the probability that it will not rain?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_4ex3ir2q">
                The probability of rain is <m>60\%</m>, or <m>0.6</m>. 
                The probability of no rain is <m>1 - 0.6 = 0.4</m>, or <m>40\%</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_ljevfg72">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0dqloijm">
                A bag contains <m>5</m> red balls, <m>3</m> blue balls, and <m>2</m> green balls. 
                If you randomly draw one ball from the bag, what is the probability of drawing a red ball?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_zjj032pg">
                The total number of balls in the bag is <m>5 + 3 + 2 = 10</m>.
                The number of red balls is <m>5</m>.
                Therefore, the probability of drawing a red ball is <m>\frac{5}{10} = \frac{1}{2} = 0.5 </m> (<m>50\%</m>).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_83eblzqj">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_rkyd0nij">
                A student is taking a multiple-choice test with <m>4</m> questions, each having <m>3</m> possible answers (A, B, C). 
                If the student guesses on all questions, what is the probability of getting at least one question correct?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_d1g5hjtv">
                The probability of getting a question wrong is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> (since there are <m>2</m> incorrect answers out of <m>3</m>).
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_k7cry5oo">
                The probability of getting all <m>4</m> questions wrong is <m>\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^4 = \frac{16}{81}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5d383nev">
                Therefore, the probability of getting at least one question correct is <m>1 - \frac{16}{81} = \frac{65}{81} \approx 0.80\%</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_raaj3pfk">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_g518uqoa">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_svk1hi2o">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_j43udmgf">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_khty7q1t">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises above or below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ca1ingts">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_41tkwbuh">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-probability">
        <title>Exercise</title>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_1efzdoa4">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_j3xt6iks">
                    A weather report states that the probability of rain is <m>0.8</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_daumiqbo">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_la7hiw5h">
                            <p xml:id="auto_uvndkmzq">
                                Should farmers prepare for rainfall?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_jx2siaq9">
                            <p xml:id="auto_tqqaht9x">
                                Explain your answer.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_acjvcsja">
                            <p xml:id="auto_vsza5bbq">
                                Does <m>0.8</m> mean it will definitely rain?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_d9d7eb81">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_6zlgdyk3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yi4j86m7">
                                Yes, farmers should prepare for rainfall.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_fy0mlbws">
                            <p xml:id="auto_bxkd36cw">
                                A probability of <m>0.8</m> means there is an <m>80\%</m> chance of rain, which is a high likelihood. 
                                It is advisable for farmers to take precautions to protect their crops and livestock from potential rainfall.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mgx8g6yj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_mjk5upla">
                                No, a probability of <m>0.8</m> does not guarantee that it will rain. 
                                It indicates a high likelihood, but there is still a <m>20\%</m> chance that it may not rain.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_lqd6xdvx">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qvsjohnv">
                    In a manufacturing factory, the probability that a product is defective is <m>0.02</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_4cfzon2v">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_hal0nsan">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ays46pp2">
                                What does <m>0.02</m> mean?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4kniy36z">
                            <p xml:id="auto_cogm32n8">
                                Out of <m>100</m> products, how many are expected to be defective?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5fqprhed">
                            <p xml:id="auto_6alefkk9">
                                Why is probability important in quality control?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_haottv2f">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_wro2cbeh">
                            <p xml:id="auto_4629jsfx">
                                A probability of <m>0.02</m> means that there is a <m>2\%</m> chance that a product will be defective.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_jkwgrlk6">
                            <p xml:id="auto_89jfacxp">
                                Out of <m>100</m> products, we can expect <m>0.02 \times 100 = 2</m> products to be defective.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_etu7fljw">
                            <p xml:id="auto_n3r880pl">
                                Probability is important in quality control because it helps manufacturers assess the likelihood of defects and take measures to reduce them, ensuring that products meet quality standards and customer satisfaction.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_ezfbxav5">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_609mv8kg">
                    A school records that the probability a student arrives late is <m>0.15</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xvlj8xc1">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_s3vdggxo">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pcp1ucgy">
                                What is the probability that a student arrives on time?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_d0t3twra">
                            <p xml:id="auto_5bw7y3lh">
                                If there are <m>200</m> students, how many are expected to arrive late?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_b12a4x3n">
                            <p xml:id="auto_oilsrq1z">
                                 Suggest one strategy the school could use to reduce lateness.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_s1dai6kd">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_yztp06j4">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2pm16kgl">
                                The probability that a student arrives on time is <m>1 - 0.15 = 0.85 (85\%)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ga60qzqo">
                            <p xml:id="auto_0nqnkoib">
                                Out of <m>200</m> students, we can expect <m>0.15 \times 200 = 30</m> students to arrive late.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_f1lme1tb">
                            <p xml:id="auto_a0tq4gzu">
                                One strategy the school could use to reduce lateness is to implement a reward system for students who consistently arrive on time, such as giving out small prizes.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_d2lbmft5">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Use visual probability scales (0 to 1 number lines) for learners to place events. Provide scenario cards with pre-written real-life situations. Use percentages alongside fractions and decimals. Connect probability to familiar contexts (weather, sports). Pair with stronger peers during group work. Provide structured worksheets with fill-in-the-blank probability statements.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Research a career that uses probability extensively (actuary, data scientist, epidemiologist, meteorologist). Calculate expected values in real-world scenarios. Explore conditional probability in medical testing (false positives/negatives). Investigate how insurance companies use probability to set premiums. Present findings to the class.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
